involvement in the pilgrimage administration in the eighteenth century and their performance of land registration and taxation as the Ottoman bureaucracy expanded in the nineteenth, to their eventual rejection of Ottoman attempts to reallocate the "empty land" they inhabited in the twentieth. She places the Syrian interior in a global context of imperial expansion into regions formerly deemed marginal, especially in relation to American and Russian empires. Ultimately, the book illuminates Ottoman state formation attempts within Bedouin communities and the unique trajectory of Bedouin in Syria, who maintained their control over land.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aBedouinszTurkeyxPolitics and government. 0aCentral-local government relationszTurkeyxHistory. 0aLand tenurexGovernment policyzTurkeyxHistory. 0aReal propertyzTurkeyxHistory. 7aHISTORY / Middle East / Turkey & Ottoman Empire.2bisacsh  aBalqa.  aBedouin.  aOttoman Empire.  aSyrian interior.  abureaucrat.  acapitalism.  acitizenship.  aproperty.  astate formation.  atribe.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2023 Englishz978311131929208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2023z9783111318912oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE History 2023 Englishz978311131913108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE History 2023z9783111318189oZDB-23-DEG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertStanford University Press Complete eBook-Package 2023z978311079132740uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978150363563040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781503635630423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781503635630/original  a978-3-11-079132-7  Stanford University Press Complete eBook-Package